description: Namhansanseong Fortress, one of the four major fortresses that guarded Hanyang in the past, is surrounded by Namhansanseong Provincial Park. To the north is Kaesong, to the south is Suwon, to the west is Ganghwa, and to the northeast is Guangzhou. Namhan Mountain Fortress is located in Guangzhou in the east. It is located on Namhan Mountain, 24km east of Seoul and 6km northeast of Seongnam City, with a total length of 12.4km and a height of 7.3m. Legend has it that 2,000 years ago, it was the royal castle of King Onjo, the son of King Dongmyeong of Goguryeo. There are also records showing that it was the Great Wall of Day built by King Wenmu of Silla in the 13th year of Hanshanzhou when the Luotang War broke out. It is said that Namhansanseong Fortress was built during the reign of King Gwanghae of Joseon (1621) after the descendants repaired the original site of the fortress several times. In 2014, UNESCO decided to inscribe Namhansanseong Fortress, a building of the Joseon Dynasty in South Korea, on the World Heritage List. Namhansanseong Fortress is also a famous sightseeing spot on foot or by car in the suburbs of Seoul, South Korea, attracting tourists all year round.
